434":"1434","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1474":"1474","1495":"1495","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","after 1474":"after 1474","1408":"1408","1528":"1528","Preston Capes, Northamptonshire, England":"Preston Capes, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cole  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Collis","meanings":["English: variant of   Coles  .","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Cowles","meanings":["English: variant of   Coles  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":25,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":98,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Coles was born in Preston Capes, Northamptonshire, England as the son of Richard Coles and Agnes. He married Alice in 1419, in Preston Capes, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died after 1474, in his hometown."},"et":{"–after 1474":"–pärast 1474","–1474":"–1474","1404–14